Name: Inside NU
Content:
Ahead of tonight’s season opener, here’s how far our staff predicts the Wildcats will go this season. 

Northwestern men’s basketball 2023-24 season prediction roundtable:

Name: Inside NU
Content: That concludes today's Coach Braun media availability.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun on using the crowd from Nebraska to learn: "I think those experiences always help. That's perspective, experience. Those are opportunities to continue to grow."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun on Kilbane's redshirt: "We intend to continue allowing that young man to continue playing at a high level. Michael Kilbane is excited to continue to help push this team to victories."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun on corner play: "Absolutely critical. If you're not playing at a high level at the corner position, it doesn't matter."

Noted that it's also about the run game and fitting gaps.

"Credit to those two [Hollis Jr. and Johnson]. Credit to the depth in that room."

Name: Inside NU
Content: More: "You never have it all figured out. You just show up each day doing your best, continuing to have a mentality of humility and growth. At the end of the day, the decisions we've made have been putting our student-athletes at the forefront of those decisions."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun on lessons learned: "It's all about your people. It's all about creating genuine relationships with players, staff and coaches. I think this group is really shining group in terms of their character, their resiliency, their togetherness."

Name: Inside NU
Content: More: "Big Ten Network, I don't know what their ratings look like, but the Braun boys are helping their ratings."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun on Chris Collins: "Coach Collins has been very supportive. Wealth of wisdom. Understanding ways that we can recruit at a really high level."

Said he's "really excited" to support the basketball team.

"Plan on supporting as much as I possibly can."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun on Wisconsin's quarterback situation: "I think you've got to prepare like you're going to see Tanner [Mordecai]. We'll certainly be mindful, and be prepared for both quarterbacks."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun on weather: "There's no doubt, when our playoff run's up in Fargo, finding ways to play in a 72-degree climate-controlled dome, there were no complaints on Saturdays about that."

Said that Big Ten football is "played outdoors" and that the team is "conscious" of weather.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun on Jaylen Pate: "It's awesome. It's what Northwestern football, this athletic department, this university is all about."

Noted him overcoming university and his "high character."

"He's turned himself into a pretty darn good Big Ten defensive end."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun on if Northwestern is worried about its standings: "Very little. They [community members] want to talk about that. The challenge to this group moving forward is leave no doubt. We handle business, let's see where this thing plays out at the end of the season."

Name: Inside NU
Content: More: "You never have it all figured out. You just show up each day doing your best, continuing to have a mentality of humility and growth. At the end of the day, the decisions we've made have been putting our student-athletes at the forefront of those decisions."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun on coaching in Camp Randall Stadium: "It'd be awesome to go into Camp Randall with this group of guys, this group of staff, and bring a victory back to Evanston."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun on improving against Big Ten West teams: "It really does come back to guys showing up, taking it one day at a time. We talk about flushing the last game."

Noted putting last year's results in the "rear view," and steady improvement from every player.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun on Braelon Allen: "Starts off with some really good tackle circuit work. He's a talented back. Really good stiff-arm. He's going to pick up four yards just by falling forward. We're going to have to do a great job in our fundamental and technique work."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun on Xander Mueller: "He's improved a ton. I still think he's just scratching the surface. That's a young man that's taking full advantage of a spring ball, of a fall camp. Has made a very conscious effort to improve."

Stressed "tempo and demeanor."

"He is flying around."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Said that a quarterback decision will be "made in the best interest of winning a football game."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun said that the team is "taking it day-to-day" in terms of Ben Bryant's status.

"I'm not willing to sit up here and say that he's not going to be available."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun on the goal-line possession: "It was very clear with Coach Bajakian that, as long as we weren't going backward, there would be an opportunity to go for it on fourth. Hindsight's 20/20. Not going to second-guess that play-calling. I feel really comfortable..."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun said that he was "involved" in the conversations with the Big Ten regarding Michigan.

"That's not in my lane," he said about the scandal.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun: "I'm excited for the challenge that's ahead."

Noted "lessons" that could be gleaned from playing in Lincoln.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun on the 14-game losing streak on the road: "This week will be unique. It'll be a bus trip. It'll look a little different. I think routine and rhythm is absolutely critical, whether it be home and away. At the end of the day, so much of it comes down to execution."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun on closing games: "It's with details. It comes down to little procedural things. For me, I've evaluated every single decisions that I've made. There's things that I can continue to improve on on the details."

Talked about revisiting the field goal block alignment.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun: "It's well-documented that we haven't played our best football on the road this season."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun on playing at Wisconsin: "Coaching Big Ten football is always really special. Having my dad at the game this past Saturday was more a testament and a credit to him than anyone else. He was dealing with some things this past week with his health."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun: "We have three guaranteed opportunities left. This group cares deeply about one another. Loves playing together. Is going to battle its tail off."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun's opening statement: "Back at it today with the group. Had productive morning meetings. An opportunity to review film with our guys, and learn from the Iowa opportunity. Got a group that is really excited about what's still in front of it. Very disappointed of the result."

Name: Inside NU
Content: David Braun set to speak to the media from the Walter Athletics Center Team Auditorium. Stay tuned for updates!

Name: Inside NU
Content: With the Big Ten West still in a topsy-turvy state, all eyes turn to Michigan-Penn State, which will go a long way in determining the outcome of the Big Ten.

Name: Inside NU
Content: A strong showing from the freshmen contingent at Big Ten Championships should have men’s tennis optimistic for spring:

Name: Inside NU
Content:
College basketball is back!

Before tonight’s tip-off, find out where each Big Ten team stands amongst it’s conference rivals heading into the 2023-24 season.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Northwestern didn’t get the No. 1 seed in the NCAA tournament, but that might not be a bad thing. Sometimes, it’s better to work with a chip on your shoulder.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
As Northwestern men’s basketball starts its 2023-24 season tonight, the Wildcats will take the floor with one new face in their starting lineup: Ryan Langborg.

Learn what drives the Princeton transfer — even after his own success — from .

Name: Inside NU
Content: A committee really said that this isn’t the No. 1 team in the country.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Tomi sacking Bryce Young is actual proof that Northwestern > Bama

Name: Inside NU
Content: It took almost 77 minutes for either team to score, but Northwestern finally broke through for the Big Ten crown.

Name: Inside NU
Content: FINALLY. Northwestern wins the Big Ten Championship off a goal from Olivia Bent-Cole in double overtime.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Northwestern has 17 corners. Maryland has 2. 75 minutes of field hockey has been played, and it is still scoreless.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Onto quarter No. 6.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Northwestern got its 13th corner of the day with 16 seconds left in the first overtime frame. It got its 14th with four seconds left but was unable to capitalize.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Make that 11. Having watched Annabel Skubisz for four years, we know talent. Klebasko is a star.

Name: Inside NU
Content: The 'Cats are up to 10 corners on today.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Seven minutes in overtime have passed and the stalemate remains.

Name: Inside NU
Content: This is just the third time ever the Big Ten Tournament was decided in overtime for field hockey.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Overtime here we are.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Eight corners and still no boards for the Wildcats.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Five minutes left in regulation, and there is still no score.

Name: Inside NU
Content: There was one green card in the first half. There have been four green cards and one yellow in the second half.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Northwestern's only ever Big Ten Tournament win was in 2014, also against Maryland, also in Ann Arbor.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Klebasko put on a show against the NU attack at the end. Still scoreless heading into the fourth quarter.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Maryland first-year goalie Alyssa Klebaska stops Ilse Tromp's shot mid-air. Have to respect it.

Name: Inside NU
Content: The Terps are up to three cards in just the third quarter, with Hope Rose drawing a yellow card. NU will enter the fourth still a player-up.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Northwestern goes man-up as Maryland takes another green card with under five left in the third quarter.

Name: Inside NU
Content: NU and Maryland both earn green cards from Lauren Wadas and Hannah Boss.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Stile 0-0 almost halfway through the third frame. Ever hear that defense wins championships?

Name: Inside NU
Content: "We just need to finish in the circle and execute out corner," head coach Tracey Fuchs said.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Scoreless at the midway point.

Name: Inside NU
Content: With a minute left in the first half, Maryland gets its first penalty corner of the day.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Olivia Bent-Cole is everywhere all at once.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Northwestern gets its third corner, but one again, Maryland is able to halt the attacking push.

Name: Inside NU
Content: A card on Maryland's Hannah Boss puts Northwestern a player up.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Neither team has broken through yet, but the 'Cats have tallied five shots and two penalty corners, while the Terps have just one shot.

Name: Inside NU
Content: No score after the first quarter. It's looking like it'll come down to a defensive battle in Michigan today.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Nearing the end of the first quarter, there is still no score, as the 'Cats and Terps go back and forth.

Name: Inside NU
Content: “Northwestern is a rather tenacious team that a) won’t give up and b) largely won’t get blown out against most opponents... However, those traits won’t fully manifest themselves unless they translate into wins,” writes .

Name: Inside NU
Content: The Wildcats lost to the Wolverines for the second straight game, prematurely concluding their postseason chase.

Name: Inside NU
Content: In 15 minutes, No. 1 Northwestern will take on No. 8 Maryland for the Big Ten Championship.

Name: Inside NU
Content: That's all from Wrigley.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Mueller on failing to string together two wins: "I don't know. We're still trying to figure it out. Bouncing back is huge, though, so we'll try to do that."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Mueller on the defense's adjustment forcing turnovers after the bye: "I think our coaches have done a great job of self-scouting and getting us ready. That was an awesome play from Theran [Johnson]."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Mueller on David Braun: "He's an awesome individual. One of the most humble guys I've ever encountered. He's a great leader and a great role model for me."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Mueller on the mindset after the offensive touchdown from NU : "We were ready to go get a win. Shame that we couldn't."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Mueller on his message to the team as a veteran with three games left in the regular season: "We know who we are, and we know we can respond. We've done that after four losses."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Mueller on mentality against a run-heavy offense like Iowa's: "We knew it was going to be a physical game, and that was a big emphasis in our gameplan."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Mueller now at the podium.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Sullivan on the then-game-tying touchdown: "We knew they were going to give us a couple different looks. They ended up zoning it off. Cam did a really good job of getting inside on his defender."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Sullivan is done. Mueller will be up next.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Sullivan on the offense's mindset following the goal-line stand: "We were still very confident in our ability to get back to the end zone."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Sullivan on the game-winning kick: "It felt like s---."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Sullivan noted that he "left plays out there" but that he thought he did well balancing staying in the pocket and scrambling.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Sullivan on staying upbeat offensively: "It's pretty obvious what our morale was. Our morale was great the whole game, and I'm proud of the guys for that."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Sullivan now at the podium.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun is done. Brendan Sullivan and Xander Mueller will speak in a few minutes.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun on Tre Tyus: "He's battling his butt off. The combination of Cam [Porter], Joe [Himon], and him is pretty special."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun on his mindset coaching after the blocked punt: "Stay the course. Keep battling. It's time to clean things up when you watch film. 

"It's not time to get frustrated in the moment. It's time for us to bull up and find a way to get a stop."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun on penalties: "I'd much rather have an aggressive football team that occasionally commits penalties than a team that plays scared and passive."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun on the sideline interference penalty: "Talked to the official, and he said that he bumped into somebody, and any time he bumps into someone he's going to throw his flag."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun on trying to form a winning streak: "I don't want to say nothing needs to change... and I know I sound like a broken record, but we need to step into the facility on Monday and get a little better each day."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun teared up when reflecting on Wrigley experience:
 
"To be honest, there's a lot of emotions pouring through me right now. My dad was at the game today. 

"This is really special. This is college football at its finest."

Said Joe Girardi was his favorite Cub growing up.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun on the "resilience" of the group: "When you have guys really playing for one another, That's sustainable. This group knows what its purpose is, and they just keep coming back."

Noted the three-and-out after Iowa's goal line stand and the return was an example.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun on the 23-yard completion to Brown late: "That's a call that I'd like to have back. More of a softer coverage zone, keep it inbounds. In hindsight, would have liked to been a little tighter and challenge these guys."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun described the locker room mood as "crushed."

"They don't just care about the result, they care about one another."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun on the offense's second half: "What clicked was our guys just staying true. We talked about it all week, we were going to have to celebrate process victories.

"Sully started to catch some rhythm (...) was really proud of the way our offense battled in the 2nd half."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun: "You're not gonna see me up here pointing any fingers at anyone but myself. This team is going to back to work on Monday, and keep doing what it's done the past few weeks: getting better every day to go battle our butts off on Sunday."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun: "Really disappointed with the result. Deeply wanted to see this team come out of Wrigley with a win. Many reasons for that, but I think you saw a team that embodied what team really looks like.

"A group that just tried to get it done through thick and thin."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun now at the podium.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Society flashed back to 1950s football with today’s outcome.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Postgame presser to start shortly. David Braun will be up first.

Name: Inside NU
Content: An ugly one that probably won’t be forgotten anytime soon.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
FINAL: Iowa 10, Northwestern 7

A last-second field goal from Drew Stevens lifts Iowa to a crucial Big Ten West win in a hideous offensive affair.

Crucial missed opportunity for NU, which tied the game late.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Northwestern fumbles, and that's game.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Iowa uses its last timeout with one second left.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Sullivan took mightily long on second down, but threw it away with one second left.

Northwestern will need a miracle.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Sullivan connects with Kirtz. Northwestern has a first down, and the clock is stopped with six seconds left on a spike.

Ball at the Northwestern 42.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Stevens' kick is a touchback.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Ferentz utilizes his second timeout before the kick.

Wouldn't be surprised to see Iowa squib this.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Stevens drills it from 53.

Northwestern will have 14 seconds left and one timeout to try to muster a comeback.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
On third-and-7, Iowa hands it to Williams, who looks like he got nothing. Kenny Soares II in on the stop.

Second TO used by Braun with 19 seconds left. This will come down to a 53-yard kick from Drew Stevens, who's 0-for-1 on the day.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Williams stutters for a gain of two. Iowa at the Northwestern 35 with 24 seconds left.

David Braun burns his first timeout.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Williams gets one yard on first down. Iowa calls a timeout with the ball at the Northwestern 37 and 29 seconds to go.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Hill drops back and finds Cael Vanderbush wide open on a corner route. A huge pickup for the Hawkeyes, who are down to the Northwestern 38.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Williams muscles his way for a first down. Iowa at its own 39.

Name: Inside NU
Content: A screen to Ragaini picks up eight yards. Several missed tackles on that one.

Name: Inside NU
Content: A short kick is fielded by Iowa. The Hawkeyes will start at their own 28.

Name: Inside NU
Content: More turf work, because of course.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Northwestern finally scored from inside the 5-yard line

Name: Inside NU
Content:
On third-and-4 from the 5-yard line, Sullivan finds Cam Johnson for a touchdown!!!

Jack Olsen's kick is good. We're all tied from Wrigley!!

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Mike Bajakian runs a QB Power, but Sullivan is swarmed along the edge by DeJean.

A questionable call to say the least.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Sullivan runs up the middle and is tripped up at the Iowa 4! Under 3 minutes left. Suddenly, this game has become riveting.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Sullivan bails from the pocket and finds Kirtz, who narrowly picks up a first down! Wildcats at the Iowa 11.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Tyus is met immediately by Deontae Craig. Third-and-5 upcoming. Have to figure this is two-down territory.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Tyus totes the rock for a gain of four yards. We're inside of 5 minutes remaining.

Name: Inside NU
Content: A short kick by Taylor is returned by Henning all the way to the Iowa 22! What a play by the All-Big Ten returner.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Best wishes to Beau Stephens, who left the game on a cart.

Name: Inside NU
Content: On third-and-8, Williams runs with a head of steam but is two yards shy. Hawkeyes will punt.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Hill is pushed again and nets two yards.

Another stoppage to fix the field at this end.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Play has resumed.

Second-and-10 with 6:19 left. Ball at the Iowa 1.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
We now have a stoppage to tamp down the field.

Sure, why not

Name: Inside NU
Content: A very valid point

Name: Inside NU
Content: Hill sneaks for a gain of maybe a half-yard.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Paramount drive coming up for Northwestern's defense, with Iowa starting inside of its own 1-yard line.

6:36 to go in this one. 7-0 Hawkeyes.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Sullivan is stopped short of the goal line.

Tremendous stand by the Iowa defense. That very well may do it.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Castro makes an enormous tackle on Porter, and it's now fourth-and-1.

Unbelievable how this is turning out.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Sullivan gets pushed from behind by Gordon, a la the Tush Push, but Nick Jackson stops him before he could break the plane. It's now third-and-1 from the 1.

"Let's Go Hawks" chants raining down.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Porter is knocked down at the 1. 8:30 to go.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Sullivan looks to Kirtz in the end zone, and DeJean is assessed for pass interference!

Northwestern has the ball at the 2. Oh my goodness.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Sullivan keeps it but is met by a pair of Hawkeyes. NU down to the Iowa 12.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Sullivan flips to Tyus, who has enough for the first down! Northwestern is at the Iowa 13 with under 10 minutes.

Name: Inside NU
Content: On third, Tyus is marked short. Sets up fourth-and-1, and the Northwestern offense is staying on the field. Biggest play of the afternoon.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Terrific catch by Johnson along the sideline to keep his knee in. A 13-yard pitch and catch, setting up third-and-4.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Sullivan hangs in the pocket and finds Porter in the flat, who's brought down by Sebastian Castro. But, holding by Josh Priebe moves the ball back.

Another killer penalty.

Name: Inside NU
Content: On first down, Iowa swarms Porter. We're under 12 minutes to go in this game.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Porter hits the hole and moves the first down. 'Cats at the Iowa 25 after strong running.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Tyus gets eight on second down. Quinn Schulte forces a third-and-2 from the Iowa 31.

Have to wonder if this is a go-for-it spot.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Sullivan escapes pressure from multiple spots and slides down after picking up no yards.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Tyus slithers through multiple tackles, stretching the run outside for a crucial first down.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Ball goes back to Lausch, who angles up the near side for three. Third-and-4 Northwestern from the Iowa 48.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Jack Lausch keeps the ball for a gain of three.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
End of the third quarter: Iowa 7, Northwestern 0

The difference so far is just the Addison Ostrenga touchdown after a blocked Hunter Renner punt.

Can the Wildcats, who have 70 total yards through three quarters, muster enough to even get on the board?

Name: Inside NU
Content: Tyus lowers his shoulder for a first down. That's Northwestern's fifth first down of the day.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Sullivan finds Bryce Kirtz for a nine-yard completion. Sets up third-and-1 after a good tackle by Jermari Harris.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Thomas Gordon drops a pass on first down.

Name: Inside NU
Content: The student completing the crossbar challenge has been just as effective as these two quarterbacks today, fwiw

Name: Inside NU
Content: Bad bounce for Taylor, as the ball checks up at the Northwestern 33.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Northwestern's defense gets off the field on third down, and Taylor will punt for the fifth time from Wrigley.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Williams gets it in his belly again, but Gallagher tackles him. It's third-and-16 Hawkeyes.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Hubbard flies in on first down to cut off the Iowa run. Strong two games for No. 91.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Holding on Tyler Elsbury pushes the ball back to the Iowa 31, and sets up first-and-20 Hawkeyes.

Name: Inside NU
Content: On third down, Williams gets past the sticks for a first down. Seventeen carries and 61 yards for No. 4 in white.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Hill narrowly escapes rush from Kenny Soares III, throwing it in the air. It was *nearly* intercepted by Rod Heard II, but somehow fell down.

Emblematic of this game.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Williams keeps his legs churning along the left side for a gain of seven.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Renner's punt bounces into the end zone. Poor special teams coverage on the back end.

Name: Inside NU
Content: David Braun makes a conservative call and sends Hunter Renner out there on fourth-and-4 from the Iowa 46.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Aaaaand it's incomplete. Another bad break for the 'Cats.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Johnson makes a low catch, and picks up the first down. However, it's under review.

Name: Inside NU
Content: On second down, Sullivan runs up the middle for eight. Tackle by Xavier Nwankpa sets up third-and-4 from the Iowa 46.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Sullivan runs right up into the pressure and loses two.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Sullivan scrambles for a first down. Nearly a late hit on Nick Jackson.

Northwestern at its own 48, and putting together a solid drive.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Porter is wrapped up by Higgins for a gain of four. Now 27 yards for the senior on the ground.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
With Castro coming in hot on a corner blitz, Sullivan hits Johnson for a first down.

First catch for No. 14.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Sullivan escapes the pocket and scrambles for no gain.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Stevens' kick goes out of the end zone for a touchback.

Name: Inside NU
Content: We have points!

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Touchdown, Iowa.

Hill finds Ostrenga wide open on the same boot concept, and it's 7-0 Hawkeyes.

Will that prove enough on the board?

Name: Inside NU
Content: Kilbane shoots down the line to stop Patterson at the 2.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Hill sneaks for a first down.

First-and-goal Iowa. This is real life.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Mueller cuts down Patterson to bring up third-and-1 from the Northwestern 5. Huge play here.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Williams works to the Northwestern 10 after multiple misses. Bryce Gallagher was there to clean it up.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Williams works upfield for the first down.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Hill works the PA Boot to find Ostrenga, who works the ball to the Northwestern 18. Gain of seven on first.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Renner's punt is partially blocked, and Iowa will start at the Northwestern 25.

First game-changing play on special teams, and it's the Hawkeyes who capitalize.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Porter is swarmed after a minimal gain, and, lo and behold, the second half begins with a punt.

Shocker.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Sullivan keeps it on a QB Draw but is tossed out of bounds by Jay Higgins. Sets up third-and-18.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Porter shoots up the middle for a solid gain, but a hold on Thomas Gordon moves it back. 

Six penalties on the Wildcats.

Name: Inside NU
Content: On the first play from the second half, Sullivan checks it down to Joseph Himon II, but Sebastian Castro meets him immediately.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Drew Stevens' kick to start the second half is fair caught by Azema, so Northwestern will start at its 25.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Northwestern lacrosse being honored at halftime. Izzy Scane needs to give a dissertation on how to play offense right now.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Will history repeat itself from the Friendly Confines??

Name: Inside NU
Content:
HALF: Iowa 0, Northwestern 0

All I can say is that I hope you took the under.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Iowa takes a knee, and we can finally end maybe the worst half in the history of football.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Renner's kick is downed with 29 seconds left at the Iowa 29.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Sullivan hits Henning in the flat, but the receiver is short and out of bounds. David Braun has to send the punt team out for the sixth time.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Iowa now calls timeout with 41 seconds left in the half. Third-and-10 will follow.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Porter hits the left side, and the clock is still running.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Yahya Black dumps Sullivan, and Iowa uses its first timeout. Second sack of the day for the Hawkeyes.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Illegal formation on Northwestern on the punt is declined. Ball at the Wildcats' 20 with 49 ticks left.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Hill overshoots Ragaini on third down down the near sideline, and another punt will commence.

Name: Inside NU
Content: A Williams draw sets up third-and-10. Ninety seconds left in the half, and still no score.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Williams is stopped by Mueller for one yard.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Luke Akers sends a boot that's fair caught by DeJean. A 48-yard punt.

Name: Inside NU

Iowa at the Northwestern 34.

Content:

Wisconsin loses to Indiana AND Nebraska loses to Michigan State...

Both teams are 5-4 and 3-3 in conference play...

With a win today, Northwestern could firmly enter the Big Ten West race

(ducks)

Payne currently in a heated discussion with the referees as displeasure with the officiating rings around the stands.

‘Cats’ Big Ten Tournament ends after one match, falling 1-0 to the Wolverines, but some questionable refereeing decisions will loom over this result.

Content:
Northwestern players appealing for a handball in the Michigan box, but after lengthy discussion amongst the officials, it’s not given.

88’ | NU 0 | MICH 1

Goldson does his best Superman impression to keep a Gajadhar volley from finding the back of the net.

‘Cats pushing for an equalizer.

82’ | NU 0 | MICH 1

Content:
Goal. Michigan.

72’ | NU 0 | MICH (1)

Content:
A *wild* scramble in the Michigan box from an Henri Richter long throw somehow doesn’t result in a Northwestern goal, despite the ball appearing to cross the line from our vantage point.

52’ | NU 0 | MICH 0

Content:
Back underway at Martin Stadium.

The heavens have opened, and the ‘Cats will be looking to open up this Michigan defense in the second 45.

Content:
The ‘Cats have been all over the Wolverines so far, but couldn’t find a goal to capitalize on their dominance in the first half.

Northwestern is currently outshooting Michigan 8-1, and most of the period was played in the vistors’ half.

Content:
Justin Weiss just hit the crossbar from 40 yards out. Wow.

After a surprising exclusion from the starting XI…

24’ | NU 0 | MICH 0

Content:
Northwestern will face Michigan for the second time in six days shortly as it looks to get payback for the 3-0 defeat it suffered Sunday.

There’s also a Big Ten Tournament semifinal spot on the line.

We’re here at Martin Stadium — stay tuned for updates!

Name: Inside NU
Content: With only a handful of games remaining in the college football season, the awards race is coming into focus.  lays out the current candidates for Big Ten Coach of the Year, and makes the case for Northwestern’s very own David Braun.

Content: gives some key insight into the Hawkeyes’ season thus far, and how they might fare on Saturday.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Northwestern will advance to its second-straight Big Ten title game thanks to a three-goal flurry in the third quarter in a 3-1 win over Ohio State.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
FINAL: Northwestern 3, Ohio State 1

The Wildcats have never won the Big Ten Tournament and the regular season title in the same season. They'll have the chance to do so against either Maryland or Rutgers on Sunday after an offensive explosion in the third quarter.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Ohio State is down but not out. With four minutes to play, they get the ball inside the circle again.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Ohio State gets on the board with a goal from Hallie Brost. Buckeyes cut the deficit to 3-1 with about six minutes to play.

Name: Inside NU
Content: They wiped the Halsey goal off the board and Northwestern really said, "And I took that personally"

Name: Inside NU
Content:
END OF THIRD: Northwestern 3, Ohio State 0
For about 40 minutes, it seemed like OSU had a legit chance to win this game or at least force OT. And then *that* happened.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Holy s----, they did it again. Three goals in three minutes. Total offensive eruption by Northwestern. Relford feeds Bent-Cole for a 1-on-1 goal, and it's 3-0.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Goal stands after a review, and NU is now in firm control of this one.

Name: Inside NU
Content: And not even 30 seconds after this, Wadas doubles the score off ANOTHER corner to make it 2-0!

Name: Inside NU
Content: ILSE TROMP WITH THE GOAL OFF THE CORNER, and Northwestern has taken a 1-0 lead late in the third!

Name: Inside NU
Content: NU forces a corner, and the 'Cats are really starting to get a head of steam. A ton of pressure on OSU's defense right now.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Northwestern's press generates two clean looks, but the 'Cats can't convert -- an infraction wipes off what looked like an apparent goal of the board.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Skubisz with ANOTHER SAVE near the side of the net on a loose ball!!

Name: Inside NU
Content: Second half is underway, with a trip to the Big Ten title game on the line.

Name: Inside NU
Content: To Brendan Sullivan: I owe you an apology, I wasn’t really familiar with your game.

Name: Inside NU
Content: The Wildcats’ season all hinges around one of the best point guards in the country.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
HALF: NU 0, OSU 0

The Buckeyes are holding up really well, and have had momentum for a good portion of the first 30 minutes. 

This could be an Annabel Skubisz legacy game though. She’s got four saves already.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Ilse Tromp’s shot off the corner (with the deflection by Halsey) goes just wide.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Another loose ball with Skubisz saving it on her back, but NU escapes. Eight minutes left in the half.

Name: Inside NU
Content: OSU with ANOTHER chance with the ball right behind Skubisz, but it gets knocked away. Another corner coming up.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Peyton Halsey gets a good look from long-range off the corner, but it’s saved on the ground.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Lauren Wadas picks up a green card.

Name: Inside NU
Content: OSU again gets inside the circle, and stays there for around 20 seconds. Two saves from Skubisz get the ‘Cats out of the jam, but the Buckeyes are having their way in the midfield right now.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Caileigh Walsh showcased her two-way ability throughout 2022-23, and another leap from her could jumpstart Northwestern’s climb up the Big Ten.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
END OF FIRST: Northwestern 0, Ohio State 0

The game is starting to open up for both teams after the Buckeyes did a great job neutralizing NU’s passing/counterattack.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Olivia Bent-Cole almost makes a game-changing move in transition, but *just* misses Chloe Relford near the back side of the goal.

NU’s first really great chance today.

Name: Inside NU
Content: In a game that started the week with the lowest over/under in history, it’s only fitting that special teams were a big topic of discussion ahead of Iowa-Northwestern.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Ten minutes in, and we’re still knotted up at zero. Transition game starting to open up for both teams, but no truly clean shots on goal yet from either team.

Name: Inside NU
Content: First penalty corner of the game goes to the Buckeyes, who are threatening inside.

Name: Inside NU
Content: OSU looked like it had a clean look at the goal just 90 seconds in, but Annabel Skubisz kicks it away.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Aaaaand they’re off in Ann Arbor.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
We’ve got field hockey action in just about five minutes! Northwestern looks to head to the Big Ten Championship with a win over Ohio State today in Ann Arbor.

Tune into BTN to watch, and here for tweets!

Name: Inside NU
Content: Ohio State and Michigan back-to-back in late November…

Content: After last night, is it not too late to add a certain No. 13 in purple and white to this list??

Content: The keys to a second-straight NCAA appearance? Doing much of what led to the first one again.

Content: Barnhizer: “The stats are at zero now. Excited for three days of practice and then start our season against Binghamton.”

Content: Langborg on tonight’s three point shooting: “It’s all about sharing the ball. If we get open looks, we’re going to hit them.”

Content: Barnhizer on being named captain: “It means everything.”

Content:
Langborg: “I had a couple bonehead fouls. I can’t put my teammates in that position.”

“You can’t play worrying about fouls because you’ll end up getting one.”

Name: Inside NU
Content: Barnhizer: “It was cool to get a start. I saw a lot of open shots because we have a ton of offensive weapons. I just got hot.”

Name: Inside NU
Content:
That’ll do it for Collins. 

Brooks Barnhizer and Ryan Langborg will be next to the podium.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Collins on Luke Hunger: “He’s a young player that’s figuring it out. We’re going to need him. I’m excited for Luke to keep getting experience.”

Name: Inside NU
Content: Collins: “We need to learn how to play aggressively but play smart.”

Name: Inside NU
Content: Collins on perimeter defense: “We need to sure that up.”

Name: Inside NU
Content: Collins on getting ready for Binghamton: “We have to continue to fine tune the defensive end. We need to sure that up a little bit.”

Name: Inside NU
Content: Collins on playing a game like atmosphere: "It was huge. To be able to play different styles was really good for us. It was good for us to see."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Collins: "We're a little bit more dynamic on offense this year."

"Our defense is the area where we need to improve."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Collins on free throws: "We got to make them."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Collins: "I thought Ty's looks tonight were good."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Collins reiterated that he had no subs tonight, which forced Barnhizer and Berry to play extended minutes.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Collins on Justin Mullins: "He's going to be a key guy for this team."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Collins: "Work in progress for sure. We got to get better, but excited to get going Monday night."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Collins: "We made great decisions. Our guys really share the ball."

He pointed to the 'Cats' 25 assists to three turnovers.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Collins: "We were severally undermanned."

Credit his guys for playing extended minutes: "You never want to do that in an exhibition, but we had no choice."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Collins sends his thoughts and prayers to Coach Knight's family.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Chris Collins at the podium

Name: Inside NU
Content:
FINAL: Northwestern defeats McKendree 85-63.

The next time the Wildcats take the floor, it counts.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
That'll do it for Barnhizer's night

The junior finished the game with 29 points, seven rebounds, four assists, four blocks and five steals.

Yeah, he's going to be a problem.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Mckendree has cut NU's lead to under 20.

'Cats leave 77-59 with 3:32 left in the game.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Northwestern is now 5-11 from the free throw line tonight.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Luke Hunger, who missed most of last season with a foot injury, checks into the game for the first time tonight

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Add a filthy block to his last few minutes.

He just sent that ball back to New Jersey.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Langborg starting to get hot.

The Princeton transfer connected on back-to-back triples to push the 'Cats' lead to 28.

Content:
Northwestern still leads by 22, but Chris Collins is not happy with his squad and calls a timeout.

62-40 NU with 12 minutes left to play.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Brooks Barnhizer is doing whatever he wants.

The junior has 12 second-half points with over 10 minutes left to play.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Northwestern is ahead 56-35 with 15 minutes left to play.

Boo Buie has not even reached double figures.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Barnhizer gets the first points of the half more than two minutes in, then pokes the ball away and throws it down. The next possession, he connects from beyond the arc.

Watch out.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Halftime: Northwestern leads McKendree 45-30.

Brooks Barnhizer leads the way with 13 points.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Ty Berry is 2-8 in from three, with a lot rimming in and out.

Not the best start as the Senior looks to find his shot this season.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Scramble for the ball finds Barnhizer, and he buries a corner three.

The junior is already in double digits.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
We may be looking at a hack-a-Blake situation this year.

The grad misses both from the line, and NU is now 4-9 from the charity stripe this game.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Langborg already has three fouls, so it has been Justin Mullins on the floor for most of the first half.

Sure looks like the Denver transfer will be the first off the bench for Chris Collins this season.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Barnhizer with the steal, and Mullins lays it in to push Northwestern’s lead back to 15 with six minutes left in the half.

Timeout McKendree.

Name: Inside NU
Content: McKendree has cut its deficit to 8, making its last four attempts from the field.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Northwestern swings the rock around, and the extra pass finds a wide open Berry, who hits from three.

23-9 NU with 11:38 left in the first half.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
BLAKE PRESTON SAYS NO SIR

The graduate transfer swats a layup off the backboard, and Justin Mullins finishes on the other end.

All three transfers are making contributions early.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
'Cats have hit four straight threes and are on a 6-0 run.

16-5 NU after five and a half minutes of play.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Buie and Langborg both can't connect from beyond the arc, but the Wildcats grab two offensive boards and Buie drills a triple.

Barnhizer follows it up with a three of his own and it is 8-3 NU with 16 minutes left in the half.

Content: Buie: "You want to stay consistent. You always want to block out the outside noise. The people from the outside, it's easy for them to judge."

Content:

Content: Buie: "The goal is to be really good in March. It's still early."

Content: Buie on the scrimmage: "I think we did really good. Obviously, there's gonna be some ups and downs."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Buie on learning from the loss to UCLA: "It's just a confidence-booster. Losing by five and knowing that we didn't really play our best, it gives a lot of confidence going into this year."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Buie on his program accolades: "I don't really chase individual goals. My only goal is to win every game that I participate in."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Buie on his decision to stay: "It was kind of easy. I was kind of just around the gym and around the guys. My heart felt here."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Buie: "I'm super excited to be back. I think we've got a chance to be really good. I think that we're really connected."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Buie on Halloween: "I'm Boo. That's what I'm here for Halloween."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Boo Buie now speaking to the media.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Collins on the new Ryan Field proposal: "I think it only enhances where we're at over here. I can't wait for that to be completed."

Joked that he hopes construction doesn't take his parking spot.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Collins on managing size in lineups: "I think last year, if you really look at it, we really played that lineup a lot."

Mentioned that NU is "counting" on Martinelli's development.

"It's not like we're going to be small the whole game."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Collins on Brian James' impact: "Coach James is part of my family. When I first got here, he was the first person I wanted to hire for all the reasons you said. He helped teach me the game."

Praised his knowledge at the high school and NBA level.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Collins on Ty Berry: "He's shot the ball really well. Certainly getting a little bit more arc on his shot was something we talked about."

Noted that Berry "did the other things exceptionally well" despite shooting woes.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Collins noted that there's "less of a sell" to recruits about coming to Northwestern after making the NCAA Tournament.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Collins on recruiting: "I don't get into much to stars and ratings. We have to stay true to the guys that fit our program. The mentality of those guys."

Also, said that he's "super proud" of fellow GBN alum and Duke head coach Jon Scheyer, who he considers a little brother.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Collins said that NU wanted to have "two high-level games" against Dayton and Arizona State.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Collins noted that all returning players had "good offseasons" and are "more seasoned leaders."

"You're talking about four guys who played a major, major role. We're really leaning on those guys to help lead the way."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Collins: "You want people to praise you for a good job. In this instance, you've got to eliminate that as well. You've got to keep an even keel."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Collins joked that he wanted to play Binghamton to induce argument between Tony Kornheiser and Michael Wilbon on PTI.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Collins noted that Northwestern wanted to play McKendree because of the team making the DII NCAA Tournament.

Called the team a "formidable opponent."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Collins: "We have 20 league games, which is a monster slate. In our non-league, we try to balance it out. How do you get the right games in the right place, and put the schedule together?"

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Collins on the scrimmage: "We were down a few guys. Just to get out there. When you play other people, you get an idea of where you're at, good and bad."

Said the team has a "long way to go" but that he liked team connection.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Collins on learning from 2017-18: "I was a young coach at that point, figuring it out... Six years older and grayer. Have to wear reading glasses now. I take a lot of responsibility for not helping that next year's team."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Collins on defense: "No one is going to be able to do what Chase did in terms of getting steals... But we hope our scheme is in place. We feel like we have to be a really good team defensive unit."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Collins: "We begin our new journey tomorrow."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Collins on what he instilled this summer: "I think you have to re-establish your habits."

Said defensive skills don't "just happen by osmosis."

Stressed building camaraderie with six new players.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Collins said that Nick Martinelli, Jordan Clayton and Parker Strauss will be out tomorrow for the exhibition game.

"We're hopeful that this is nothing long-term."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Collins: "I know our guys are looking forward to not playing against each other."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Chris Collins now speaking to the media at Welsh-Ryan Arena.

On the snow: "It confirmed that it's basketball season. We're excited to get going."

Said the team "has a lot to work on" in the preseason.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Before the Wildcats travel downtown to the Friendly Confines, hear from David Braun about keeping intensity up after a huge win, development of Northwestern’s D-line, preparing for Cooper DeJean and even the Braun family’s Halloween costume plans.

Name: Inside NU
Content: As Northwestern takes on Iowa at Wrigley, the age-old saying of “defense wins championships” comes to mind.

Name: Inside NU
Content: With meaningful competition on the horizon, the October NAC offered a gauge for ‘Cats to figure out where they stand.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Northwestern volleyball played eight sets against Big Ten foes this past week.

Name: Inside NU
Content: That concludes today's media availability.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun said he has a sweet tooth.

"When I get home, their candy will probably be hidden."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun on A.J. Henning having six targets: "I think that's always something that's on the forefront of Mike's mind. I think some of the specific scheme was more tailored to what we were seeing out of Maryland. We know the playmaker that A.J. is."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun on Joseph Himon II: "It's awesome. That dude was such a headache such spring ball to me as a defensive coordinator. Gave our defense fits this fall camp. You can see the way that our guys respond when Joe gets the ball in space."

Praised the blocking efforts downfield.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun on special teams: "Expecting them to continue doing what they're doing."

Said that Jack Olsen "continues to play at a really high level" and called Olsen, Halkyard and Renner "pros."

"They have their routine. They stick to it. They take ownership in their craft."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun said that he doesn't have any Halloween plans, but that his wife Kristin has Mario costumes lined up for his kids.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
More: "We're going to have to do a great job of focusing on the details."

Said that "competitive demeanor" will have to be met with "poise."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun on the lack of a win streak: "I'm proud of the way that we've responded after losses, for sure. What a great opportunity for us to keep momentum. So much of it is isolating one game at a time. It's going to be absolutely critical that we completely put Maryland behind us."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun on the use of practice to evaluate players: "I think we're in a unique setting. It's going to take all of us. Owning your role."

Said that Kilbane "helped us in a big way" to beat Maryland.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
More: "He's a dude."

Noted that NU will need to be creative in certain looks to avoid return opportunities.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun on Cooper DeJean in the return game: "My first conversation was with Matt Entz. I really would've appreciated if Matt could've closed that so we wouldn't have to do deal with that now."

Called him a "model" of what Iowa stands for.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun: "We're going to have a great week of preparation. That starts this afternoon."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun on the attitude: "We've got to respond. How are we going to respond to success? How are we going to respond to people talking about bowl games, and the Big Ten West? Tuning it all out, guys. It's interference. What do we need to do today to position ourselves?"

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun: "I feel like great D-line play is guys playing free. It's, 'Man, I'm going to play vertical, knockback, aggressive football.'"

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun: "If you watch me in D-line drills, I might stick around for a while. I'm pretty passionate about that position."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun on Michael Kilbane and Dylan Roberts: "Part of it was out of necessity in terms of where we're at from a depth perspective. They earned that opportunity with their practice habits, with the way they're performing on scout team."

Said it's not based on "one flash practice."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Noted Sullivan's need to be a great decision-maker and game manager against the Hawkeyes.

"There's no doubt in my mind that he's going to continue to put our team in a lot of situations to win football games."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun on Iowa's defense: "We'll all be challenged in so many ways. This defense is a model for consistency. It's impressive. We're going to have to detail our work this week."

Noted that Sullivan needs to focus on taking care of the football, his eyes and his process.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Also praised Bajakian's play-calling for allowing Sullivan to get the ball out more quickly.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun on conversations with Brendan Sullivan: "The first thing that I told him was that I was proud of him. You evaluate where he needs to be better. Coach Bajakian expects a lot out of Brendan. I think we did a really good job this week of getting Sully comfortable."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun on Aidan Hubbard: "Really proud of Aidan. I think what we're starting to see are the things that we've seen out of Aidan in practice on a consistent basis. Has really developed as a pass-rusher."

Noted that he lacked "urgency" and "motor" in the spring but refined those.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun on differences in playing at Wrigley: "We'll have to be very strategic in that."

Noted that both teams will be on the same sideline, as was the case in 2021.

"I firmly am confident that our guys will handle it well."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun said that NU "anticipated" that Maryland was going to pass on fourth down.

Gave credit to Xander Mueller for the key stop.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
More: "You look at some of those guys lined up, you're going: 'I'll take this group any day."

Noted that the D-line "will be tested in a big, big way" against the Hawkeyes.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun on the defense's goal-line stand against Maryland: "What that D-line room has been able to do this season is such a reflection of what you hope is happening all over this team right now. It's banked reps from us double-repping during fall camp. It's developmental reps."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun on the over/under being 29.5: "Honestly, I know it sounds super cliche: I wasn't aware of that."

Noted that the team has "all the extra motivation it needs."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun on playing at Wrigley Field: "I know that I've had a lot of these moments in the last year, but it's another pinch yourself moment."

Said that the first baseball game he went to was at the Friendly Confines.

"What a unique, special experience."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun on Ben Bryant's availability: "Do not anticipate Ben playing this week."

Noted that he's "progressing," but that "he is working his but off." Stressed that the team anticipates him returning this year.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun: "We know the challenge that is ahead."

Talked about Iowa's fundamentals, technique and physicality.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun's opening statement: "Exciting time to be around the facility right now. Team that battled on Saturday, found a way to get a big win. We were back at it this morning evaluating the film."

Said that the team is getting better, but that it's "clear" that there's room to grow

Name: Inside NU
Content: David Braun set to speak to the media from the Walter Athletics Center shortly.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun on Azema: "When I speak to pro scouts about Coco, I tell them that if you get this guy on your team, he is going to make everyone better."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun: "There's so much about this place that makes it special."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun: "The belief between one another is unshaken. Our team showed up on Sunday after Lincoln, took responsibility, and said we need to find a way to play winning football."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun on how he would describe Brendan Sullivan: "Warrior"

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun: "The challenge moving forward is putting this game behind us and getting ready for Iowa."

Content: Braun: "I cannot express how proud I am of these guys. They just went back to work."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun: "Our offense carried us in the first half."

Content: Braun: "Today was a perfect reflection on what this group stands for and what they embody week-in and week-out."

Name: Inside NU
Content: In his weekly media availability, David Braun covered all three phases, and then some.

Name: Inside NU
Content: As Northwestern claimed its first Big Ten regular season title since 2013 over the weekend, the ‘Cats showed why they are the No. 1 team.

Name: Inside NU
Content: The 7-footer has the potential to indicate how the basketball season will go for the ‘Cats.

Name: Inside NU
Content: To clarify, Braun was asked about NU wearing black (and not purple) for three straight home games, including this upcoming weekend against Maryland.

Name: Inside NU
Content: To clarify, Braun was asked about NU wearing black (and not purple) for three straight home games, including this upcoming weekend against Maryland.

Name: Inside NU
Content: That ends today's presser.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun on the remaining goals: "The goal moving forward is finding a way to beat Maryland. All of our efforts and energy have to go into getting a win back at Ryan Field, which is an opportunity we're really excited about."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun on experience on defense: "It's a credit to our players. It's a credit to that defensive staff. Unique circumstances."

Said that players have earnestly asked him how he's doing, which only motivates him as a coach further.

Called Coco Azema's tape "energizing."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun on team resilience: "It's just the character of the group. We all know this is a unique season for a lot of different reasons. I think you've got a group that steps back in the facility, owns the previous week and attacks the next opportunity."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun on Cam Porter: "I had the opportunity to visit with Cam a couple of times. He is the ultimate team player. Embodies selflessness. At the end of the day, would Cam like to touch the ball 30 times a game? Absolutely. Cam is always going to put the team first."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun on Brendan Sullivan: "He's continued to get better and better each week. I see a young man that battles. That's all you can ask out of your quarterback."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun on better tight end blocking: "The conversation is about eliminating gray."

Noted that the pre-snap movement altered how the block was executed.

Said that the team will take "extreme ownership" about its own mistakes and won't blame officials.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun on uniforms: "That is a question that I don't feel positioned to answer right now."

Said he would want to spend more time aggregating information (largely via time in the program) before weighing in).

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun on the Wildcats' secondary: "I think you see a group that's continuing to find more and more confidence. Finding a certain rhythm with one another. I think you find a group that is responding to some challenges that we've put in front of them."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun on deciding carries/touches: "I'm not mandating who's in, who's out. I trust our offensive staff to make in-game decisions as they continue to manage our offense."

Name: Inside NU
Content: On in-game conversations: "At the end of the day, considering the context of the situation and the way all of this happened, I was never going to be a micro-manager of the offense. In-game, it's more strategy, time management, things that I'm seeing."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Particularly stressed keeping the ball ahead of the sticks.

"Those are things that Mike and I have had conversations about. We're taking active steps to ensure that those areas improve."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun on talking to Mike Bajakian: "Those conversations happen weekly. There's not a single person in this facility that doesn't want to see that area of our offensive operation continue to improve. As you evaluate those scenarios, we certainly have to execute."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun said that he did re-watch the game against Maryland last year in College Park.

"They do a good job of mixing inside zone, outside zone, some gap scheme. Enough element of quarterback run game that keeps you honest."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun on preparing for Maryland's offense: "They're really good. Well-structured run game. A bunch of juniors and seniors up front. A very deep, talented wide receiver room. A quarterback that operates at an extremely high level."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun on offensive play: "I thought Sully battled his tail off, and found ways to create some plays. We've got to do a better job of protecting Sully."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun added that "nothing's changed" since the early outlook, which seemed more promising.

"We're going to stay optimistic from our rehab approach."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun said there's no update on Ben Bryant:

"We're very confident that Ben will be back at some point this season."

Called it a "fickle deal" in terms of his injury, with day-to-day operation.

"He's hungry to get back."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun on starting Jackson Carsello at center: "We'll evaluate that day-to-day. Jackson had a great two weeks of practice."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun on special teams: "The way that those guys performed in terms of being able to create advantageous field position, Jack [Olsen] being able to get us on the board, Will [Halkyard] from a snapping standpoint. Probably something that we could point out every single week."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun on the same mistakes: "There's been elements in terms of our protection that have been clicking, for sure."

Said the team has to get better at dealing with pressure looks.

Noted that there have been "bright spots" in terms of pass rush. Called OL/DL "points of emphasis."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun said that the team is "amped up" and "ready to grow from" the loss to Nebraska.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun on team morale: "It [the mood] is different [than other games]. I think you have a football team right now that has started to really find their confidence, their identity."

Noted that the team "left every ounce of their being out on that field."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun called the team "intense" and said that it knows its best football is ahead of it.

Name: Inside NU
Content: David Braun's opening statement: "Back in the facility yesterday. Our guys were back at it this morning for morning meetings. Did not get any easier yesterday, going back and reviewing the film. You have a group that is disappointed in the result, but also very hungry."

Name: Inside NU
Content: David Braun set to speak to the media shortly from the Walter Athletics Center Team Auditorium. Stay tuned for updates!

Name: Inside NU
Content: “For NU players to still commit backbreaking penalties, miss blocks and not secure ball-carriers is, ultimately, a reflection of a coaching staff that has yet to actually fix the team’s most basic issues,” writes  after NU’s loss to UNL.

Name: Inside NU
Content: That wraps up today's pressers.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Azema on translating aggression: "I see myself as a tone-setter. I feel like guys feed off of that."

Talked about Braun's mentality of celebrating small victories and physicality.

"It makes the offense think a little bit more."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Azema on special teams: "Guys embracing their role. At the end of the day, that's a third of the game. Guys don't bat an eye. I love it. Why not start the game off? Why not be on special teams?"

Name: Inside NU
Content: Azema on the defense keeping high spirits despite the offense's struggles: "At the end of the day, it's a simple game: if the other team doesn't score, we win. We have to go look in the mirror, and go back to the drawing board."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Azema on tackling Heinrich Haarberg: "Shoutout Cole Freeman. He's out scout team quarterback right now. He's running the option the whole week for us. He prepared us definitely for it."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Azema on defensive improvement: "I think the physicality. We came out and set the tone. It's a big emphasis: not letting the offense fall forward."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Azema on Devin Turner: "Devin acts like a coach's kid. Devin loves the game of football. He puts the preparation. At the end of the day, he should have about five picks right now. He's always in the right spot."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Azema on the safety group's performance: "We're the heartbeat of the team. We have great depth in the room, we rotate guys, and we know that everyone can make a play."

Added that "we've got to keep the pedal down."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Coco Azema now speaking.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Kirtz on the locker room mood: "The mood is not high, obviously. We didn't come here to lose. Guys aren't too happy about the way things went."

Noted Braun's 24-hour rule of flushing results.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Kirtz on not capitalizing on his 66-yard catch: "It's definitely frustrating. You definitely want to capitalize off a big, explosive play like that. It takes the momentum away, almost. It's hard to bounce back from that."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Kirtz on his confidence in Brendan Sullivan: "He's definitely poised. Every time he steps on the field, he wants to score. You love to see that, because in an away game, it's hard."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Kirtz on drives stopping short: "Really just in practice, we've just got to prepare better. Self-inflicted wounds is no way to go about a game."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Kirtz on the offense: "Our focus point was playing physical, starting fast. I just felt like we weren't physical enough."

Called the sack number "unacceptable."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Bryce Kirtz now at the podium.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun on Ben Bryant: "We do expect to get Ben back at some point."

Said that he didn't have a specific update or timetable. Added that it's "hard to say" if he'll be ready for Maryland.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun on road struggles: "We had a focused a team. A team in the locker room that was ready to roll. I thought our group did a great job of handling this environment. They stared that thing down. If we can continue to have that approach on the road, the wins will come."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun on run defense: "It'll be interesting to go back and watch the film. Overall, I thought that group battled their tail off. Eleven guys swarming."

Said the defense played with "edge" and "urgency."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun on Hunter Renner: "Awesome. Really proud of our kicking game and how we executed."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun on Richie Hagarty not making the trip: "We were really hopeful that he would. Sometimes those injuries, there's an ebb and flow. As we got later in the week, we knew we weren't gonna make it happen, but optimistic we'll make it happen for Maryland."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun on Devin Turner: "It's just him honing into his process. That's a young man that continues to grow, continues to improve."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun on Brendan Sullivan's play: "There wasn't a consideration [in making a change]. I'm proud of Sully."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun on offensive line play: "The O-Line plays a critical piece in that. So do the 'backs. So do the wide receivers. So does the quarterback."

Said there are "so many pieces" and that "it's everyone that plays into that."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun on not capitalizing on Heard's pick: "In hindsight, it's huge. We're going to continue to harp on it. We've got to find ways to turn that into seven points."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun called Sullivan's interception "inconsequential."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun on the decision-making to end the first half: "There were some opportunities at the end of the half, where we could've called some timeouts to give ourselves more time. I didn't feel like it was the time to give them more time to process offensively."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun on tight end penalties: "We've got to continue to evaluate it. You've got to get your hands inside."

Said there's holding on "every single play" but that the team has to have  a "feet-first mentality" for blocking outside.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun: "We've got to continue to find ways to stay efficient, and to stay ahead of the sticks. Especially in the red zone when those gains were stalling out, going negative."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun: "This group is up to the challenge. We've found a way to win three games up to this point. We should expect to have an opportunity."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun: "Proud of our effort. Certainly not satisfied with the result. Disappointed with the result."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun in his opening statement: "You have a locker room in there right now that is crushed. This team, this program, came into Lincoln today expecting to win a football game. We challenged them to play for four quarters."

Said the team "played their tails off."

Name: Inside NU
Content: David Braun will speak to the media shortly.

Name: Inside NU
Content: It was an up-and-down game for Northwestern in more ways than one.

Name: Inside NU
Content: The Wildcats remain winless away from Ryan Field.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
FINAL: Nebraska 17, Northwestern 9

An ugly affair by both sides ends in favor of the home team. Eight sacks and a very slow start from Brendan Sullivan doomed a strong defensive effort, including two takeaways.

The Wildcats drop to 3-4 and 1-3 in conference play.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Nebraska takes a knee, and Braun doesn't call a timeout. This one is over.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
With the game on the line, Sullivan is crushed. Immediate pressure up the middle ruined the play.

That'll do it from Lincoln.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Sullivan rolls left and is nearly picked by Phalen Sanford. This will be the game on fourth-and-17.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Matt Rhule uses his first timeout of the half with 1:33 left.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Sullivan is flushed from the pocket and chucks one deep to nobody. It's now third-and-16; would have to think NU needs at least eight.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Sullivan is sacked by Gifford, marking the seventh (!) sack of the day. Moves NU to second-and-16. Killer.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Sullivan threads the needle to Kirtz for a pickup of 13. Wildcats going quickly.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Sullivan races for a gain of 10 on a scramble.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Henning makes a fair catch at his 13. The Wildcats will have 2:59 to drive down the field, score and convert a two-point conversion.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Haarberg takes off and runs on third but is met in the hole by Gallagher. Second timeout utilized by Braun.

UNL will punt with 3:06 remaining.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Johnson runs again for three, and Braun utilizes his first timeout left with 3:12 to go.

Will be third-and-4 following this stoppage.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Emmett Johnson pushes forward for three yards. Inside of four minutes left.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Haarberg goes off tackle on zone read for a gain of 16. Another big run for No. 10 in red.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
A hold on the Huskers puts the ball at the UNL 24 with 4:39 to go. Northwestern still down by eight.

That last drive may prove to be a killer.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Sullivan is flushed with pressure and eventually brought down by James Williams. Renner punts with under five minutes left.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Porter is short of the sticks on third down, and a facemask on Thomas Gordon makes it now third-and-18. Cataclysmic.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Johnson digs out a slant to establish third-and-3.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Porter works east-west but loses two. Under seven minutes left.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Working against the blitz, Sullivan buys time and finds Cam Johnson open for a first down. Huge conversion, and a pickup of 14.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Lenhardt totally stuffs a Henning jet sweep. Loss of four, creating third-and-9.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Sullivan links up with Henning on a tunnel screen to get five.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Henning makes a fair catch at the 12. Northwestern trails by eight with 8:39 left.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Gallagher locks down Fidone II on third down. Great play by the captain to get NU the ball back.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Haarberg throws across his body to Fidone II to net three. It's a crucial third-and-5 coming up for the Huskers.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Grant picks up three, but more clock ticks off. Under 10 minutes to go.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Emmett Johnson rips off a 10-yard run following a whiff from Gallagher.

Name: Inside NU
Content: From the 25, Haarberg runs for five.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Olsen nails it. It's 17-9 Huskers with 11:09 left.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Sullivan throws to Marshall Lang in the flat, but he's dropped by Malcolm Hartzog. Olsen will kick from 25.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Sullivan runs for a loss of two. A NU tight end was left alone to the right side.

Third-and-goal.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Tyus gets the ball and gets four. NU at the UNL 5 after previously being at the 9.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Sullivan evades a corner blitz and drops one right in the bucket to Kirtz! Gain of 66 yards.

Northwestern at the UNL 5. Touchdown is needed here.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Sullivan and Kirtz are off again on first, missing on a slant.

Content: As Northwestern begins the back half of its season, read what interim head coach David Braun told the media on Monday afternoon.

Name: Inside NU
Content: That'll wrap us up here.

Name: Inside NU
Content: "Whoever's holding this position going forward, that's what you can count on."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun on pitching recruits despite not knowing his own future status: "It's the same thing that we tell our players: control the controllables. Northwestern offers one of the best degrees one will find, playing in the Big Ten."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun on Xander Mueller: "I love the way that young man approaches practice. There's a consistency, a focus there. Xander Mueller is someone that fully embraces and invites coaching."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun on the benefit of the second half of the season: "I think it's an opportunity to reflect on our experience, take full ownership, and identify areas we need to challenge ourselves."

Noted clock management, communication as areas he could improve on.

Name: Inside NU
Content: On keeping a balanced gameplan if Brendan Sullivan starts vs. Nebraska: "Something I've challenged our team on is our pre-snap procedure. Making sure our communication from the sideline to our team... that everything is perfect."

Name: Inside NU
Content: On Richie Hagarty's injury status: "We anticipate that Richie will play."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun on stopping Nebraska QB Heinrich Haarberg: "You've got to play with great leverage, and you've got to tackle. He's got the ability to be extremely explosive.

"I've been really impressed with his ability to operate within the scheme."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun on facing the Nebraska crowd: "It all roots back into our practice prep. Even last week, we were pumping crowd noise into our practices.

Complimented Mike Bajakian and Kurt Anderson for prepping the offense for that atmosphere through non-verbal communication.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun on his growth as a head coach through the first half of the season: "I feel like I've grown exponentially. Your greatest growth comes in situations of adversity. There's a lot of growth left, there's a great group around me, and I continue to assess ways I can improve."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun on Bryant, Henning and Lausch's injury statuses: "We anticipate A.J. will be good to go. As is Jack. Ben continues to progress, not sure what his status will be, but he's progressing."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun: "We invested last week in Nebraska prep, and then had an opportunity to have a little bit of downtime over the weekend."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun: "Coming off a bye week, really proud of the way your guys handled last week. We invested in some developmental opportunities for our entire roster, specifically guys that haven't gotten in-game reps."
